 fashion to the Lemmings games to traverse through every nook and crany of the map, collecting gems and other valubles which increase your highscore if you manage to successfully get them home.\n\nI bought this game myself shortly after coming into contact with the developer on steam. He was very kind and so I thought I would do my part and at least give his game a go. I'm glad I had. I had issues at first with the key bindings, but upon asking him about it, the game was soon updated to include tool-tips to remind the player of the keybindings. I have never met a developer who is so considerate of the needs of his customers.\nThis brings me on to his dedication. This game appears to be, despite what the update logs say, recieving updates (be it minor or large) on almost a daily basis. I can't deny that I'm surprised. I've genuinely been given the impression that he really, and I mean REALLY, cares about his work.\n\nMore about the game though. It plays a little clunky, I have had troubles from time to time controlling my miners but that may be entirely down to how incompetent I am at the game. I don't believe the game looks particually polished graphically and I can't help but feel like the game would have been better in early access, in the sense that the developer is planning for so many more features to be added that it almost seems like it's not quite finished. However, for this kind of game, graphics don't matter anywhere near as much as they might in other games.\nNon-the-less, I believe the game for such a small price of \u00a34.99 is definitely worth a shot (there's always the refund system if it doesn't turn out to be what you're looking for), there's a lot of fun to be had. Perfectionists will love doing the same levels in order to get the highest scores possible and casuals will love to pop on, play a short game and come off again. It really does feel like a new lemmings game but with more replayability, so if you were looking for more Lemmings or just a 